description.text:
Batch of Parts to expand Meccano Erector models and projects.
Intended for building Robot Projects.

I saw meccano space models on the internet. But only a few minimal meccano parts on thingiverse. I thought that I could do better. So, I designed and printed my own parts one weekend. I also decided to design my own special parts and models.

Obviously, erector parts (including 3mmx10mm bolts and nuts) are needed to build Models with these printed parts.

title: Prusa / Prusa i3/ Mendel / Reprap / Printrbot DDE Spring Lever Drive v1.6, UBIS hot End, Others with Mods

description.text: I really liked the simple system used on the new Replicator extruder set up so decided to re-create it for the Printrbot and generic RepRap style machines. This unit is designed to fit a UBIS style hot end, but can be easily modded to take a J head or whatever else. This will bolt straight onto a Prusa i3, and should fit any other generic Reprap style machine, maybe with minor mods.. This is a new iteration of my previous design with improvements. Make sure you print the main "block" in ABS. I tried it in PLA and it went rubbery and loose after about 20 prints. The 1.6 includes a re-designed extruder mount, a filament guide, better spring mount, a cleaner drawing and a slightly tweaked lever. A new change is a much stronger shaft area around the 608ZZ bearing. Earlier versions had a tendency to flex and bend. You'll need a 608ZZ bearing and some sort of spring. This one I salvaged from a dead printer, which are full of cool springs. You want a fair bit of tension on the lever, so you'll need a pretty strong spring. There's a few M4 nuts and bolts there too. I used allen screws on the attachment to the head because it's easier getting an allen key in there rather than a phillips head, plus they look cooler. The new version now mounts the extruder on 2 x M4 screws. I found the M3's on the original were just too wimpy to hold the extruder firm for a long time and had to be re-tightened on a regular basis. The new M4's solve this. This is a heavily remixed version of this unit - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:155711 This is also a GREAT extruder, I was running it for a while and it's a huge improvement over the stock piece.

comments.text: Ah yeah,. on the lever bit, I made that with about 70% fill, 3 perimeters.. To make it work with 3mm filament you can just drill out the holes and it will work OK.

title: Mars Pathfinder and Sojourner
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a model of the Mars Pathfinder and Sojourner lander and rover which landed on Mars in 1997. Pathfinder prints in one piece in its folded configuration. Once the support material is removed, the the side panels can be opened and closed. The Sojourner rover can fit inside the model while folded.

***Be careful when first unfolding the model as support material is printed inside of the hinges. Do not force a panel open. If one gets stuck, use pliers to carefully rotate the axel itself and it should come loose. Once opened for the first time, the panels should be able to move freely.

author: shivinteger

print_settings.Notes:: https://hackaday.io/project/11429-internet-of-things-microscope

description.text:
This is a open source project that is pioneering a mixture of 3D printed parts and electronics. This Microscope has a significant amount of parts 3D printed.

This project has a very detailed build log on Hackaday. Please follow the link to learn more. It is currently entered into the 2016 Hackaday prize.

https://hackaday.io/project/11429-internet-of-things-microscope

We are building a low cost IoT microscope based on the Raspberry Pi 3. Using easily changeable glass objectives. This microscope will provides various magnification. (40x, 100x, 400x).

The Raspberry Pi 3 will provide the necessary I/O pins for control of the stepper drivers and Pi camera, and will also facilitate the connection to multiple devices via a WiFi connection. Since it also has a built -in full size HDMI port, you can also simply hook the microscope to a TV or computer screen to view the camera.

Features include:

Uses common microscope eyepiece and objectives. At the moment that includes a 10x eyepiece and a 10x objective for a total of 100x magnification.

A stepper controlled Z axis.

Remote WiFi control of Z Stepper and camera feed

Dimmable LED light

A slide platform that was printed solid with added spring loaded metal slide holders.

Side facing focusing knobs on smooth running metal ball bearings.

A 160mm 3D printed tube to match the focal lengths of the glass lenses.

Built in Li-poly battery to run the scope with out power infrastructure, Also a large solar array to power it in remote areas.

Enjoy!

Printrbot

Simple White

Notes:

Print any optical elements in black PLA or ABS.

Print the slide platform solid

The Motor mount is the only part that needs support and should also be printed solid. All other parts can be printed with a 20 percent infill.

For a complete parts list please visit:

https://hackaday.io/project/11429-internet-of-things-microscope

ZMR 250 Heavy Duty Landing Gear Remix.

Had issues with bounce / flex, so reinforcement was added. Not terribly heavy and is quite durable.

Print 100% infill with PLA.

title: Wanhao Duplicator 6 blower fan upgrade for extruder and part cooling

description.text:
This set of parts allows you to improve the cold end cooling as well as the part cooling. The blower fans move much more air that the stock axial fans especially for the cold end cooling. No loss of travel is a feature of this design as well. Both Nozzle and ExtruderCooler mount re-using the stock screws. Wire management clips are included in the design.

Note that the Nozzle is not fully optimized for air flow as I don't have simulation tools for this. I have found it works quite well in my testing and is much better than the stock cooler.

The fans used are the Delta BFB0412HHA and are available from Digikey:
http://www.digikey.com/product-detail/en/delta-electronics/BFB0412HHA-A/603-1363-ND/
The fans are secured to the printed parts using #2 wood screws.

These fans are 12V and so modification to the power supply is needed. Luckily the Wanhao D6 uses a low side switch to drive the fans. This means that the negative terminal of the fan connector on the print head can be used as is. A 12V supply is needed to power the fans. The clips have a mounting point for 22ga wire to run from the electronics enclosure to the print head. The power lead provides power to both fans.

The cable clips are based on:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1590264
and are edited to increase the grip on the tubing.

I cut the connectors from both of the stock fans. The negative (black) wire from the stock connector is soldered to the negative wire on the blower fans. The positive (red) wires from both fans are soldered together and to the power lead that is routed from the electronics enclosure in the bottom of the printer.

To generate the 12V supply, I used a LM7812 linear regulator in the datasheet standard configuration. The TO220 package was used and mounted on an old 486 heatsink I had lying around. Input to the 12V regulator connected to the 24V header on the control board in the D6. Maximum current for both fans is 0.16A so the power dissipation in the regulator is ~1.92W which is why a fairly good heatsink is needed. You might be able to bolt the regulator the case, but I have not tested this.

Printer:

Wanhao D6

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm layer 0.4mm width

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Supports are needed. Extend from bed only, internal supports will be impossible to remove.

Print the Nozzle part with the top towards the bed. The Nozzle and ExtruderCooler parts also needs to be printed in ABS or other high temperature plastic. I printed the Nozzle and ExtruderCooler in FormFutura ApolloX which is an ASA based plastic. PLA WILL melt if used for ether of these parts.

The TubeHolder and Wire Holder parts should be printed in PETG or equivalent plastic. While PLA won't melt in this application, the snap fit of the teflon tube holder and wire holder requires quite a bit of spring back.

description.text:
This is a watch band/case for an arduino LED watch that I designed some time ago. You can find all the details of this project at my instructables page here:
http://www.instructables.com/id/Arduino-LED-Watch/

This was my first attempt at a 3D printed enclosure for my watch. You can print the entire thing as one piece and remove or add links as needed. The complete watch will fit a wrist that is about 7 inches in circumference. Or just print all the parts individually and snap them together.

The clasp is a simple hook and loop design. Depending on your print settings, you might need to do some shaving and sanding to get it to close properly. I'm open to any suggestions to improve it!

I originally made the top plate out of tinted plastic, but you could also print one using any type of transparent filament. I wanted to avoid using screws, so the plate is just press fit into place. You can also add some white glue if you want. Don't use superglue, just in case you need to take it apart later on.

Use a small amount of superglue to attach the buttons to the inside of the watch body. (See image)

The overall length turned out to be around 180mm for my toothbrush. It can be easily adapted for any length by cutting the brass tubing to the length you need.

The brass tubing i used is from a hobby shop, 4mm outside diameter. My pack had 3, 0.45mm wall, 30cm long tubes. No other hardware was required to assemble this.

A bit of patience goes a long ways!

title: Led Ring Light DeskLamp Conversion
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
In the past i have done an LED conversion of an inexpensive halogen desklamp. It worked out ok, but lacked the brightness or variability to cover the range of brightness i needed.

I designed this replacement lamp head around a set of led ring lights i found on ebay. Meant for automotive application, i naturally saw other uses for them!

This is a large print, in area and time. Not for the faint of heart.
The electronics to drive and control it are still a work in progress.

See this object for a small version: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1845911

The concept is to "step up" the brightness by turning on more and more leds giving a range of 11 steps ( in my design ) of brightness.
The four(4) ring lights are 90mm, 110mm, 130mm and 150mm in diameter.
The donor lamp base has 6mm extensable rods with a double D end for the screws that transmit the power up from the base. Found my donor lamp at a thrift store cheap!

The electronics are based around an Arduino MiniPro, and a 4 channel FET switch board ( see ebay link ). Additionally needed are a rectifier / filter board, to convert the lamp AC to raw DC, as well as a couple of small regulators, 1 for the lamps (12v) , and 1 for the Arduino (5v). Plans are also to add a rotary encoder, to control the brightness.

These are "representative" of the parts i bought, not the actual ones.
http://www.ebay.ca/itm/Four-Channel-4-Route-MOSFET-Button-IRF540-V2-0-MOSFET-Switch-Module-For-Arduino-/171915397754?hash=item2806f4ca7a
http://www.ebay.ca/itm/KY-040-Rotary-Encoder-Module-for-Arduino-AVR-PIC-/401150412050?hash=item5d666d8512:g:c7wAAOSwMNxXXoIk
http://www.ebay.ca/itm/Car-Angel-Eyes-Halo-Ring-Fog-Headlight-White-Light-2x-90mm-1210-3528-24-LED-/172265849655?hash=item281bd84337:g:WgoAAOSwnNBXaxys&vxp=mtr

Not knowing exactly how large a volume i needed, i made the head shell a bit larger then it probably needed to be.
Again a work in progress....... and i may redesign the shell.

Ok added the "schematic" , quick hand drawn one..... and the arduino code i am using right now. It's functional and responsive. It just takes a second to fire up, but i'm looking at that little issue as time permits.
I also added the little PCB holder i used for my project. Most likely you will have to design your own to suit your needs.
The encoder did NOT have a mounting hole and i just used a soldering iron, on / at about 430F 220C to "make" a hole in the shell where i wanted it mounted. Use an OLD iron tip.

Printer:

Mendel Max 1.5

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.3mm

Infill:

15%

Notes:

Print the ring support head, concentric slot side up, and using support for the square pocket at the back. I had to orient it diagonal on my 230mm x 230mm print bed. It is almost 245mm long, and may not fit on a lot of print beds. :(

The head shell print was time consuming, printed hollow side down, on a raft, with pillar supports, is the longest print i have done to date. Digging the support out was not fun.

Used 2 perimeters on both objects.

Both pieces turned out ok.
Be careful triming and removing support material, Nuff said....

Careful removing the support from the double D slots for the rods from the base, it's easy to clear too much plastic out. I used an additional flat washer under the screws for the rod wire connections to spread the load to the plastic.

The led rings are a snug fit into the grooves of the head, and are held in place by a few SMALL dots of RTV silicone around the rings. ( Don't go crazy with the silicone )
The wires pass thru the hole back to the electronics and power.

A set of M3 15mm cap screw washers and nut are used to hold the shell to the head. Yes i "stuck" the nuts down with silicone so they don't run away on me....

When i have more detail i will post additional info. Again a work in progress.....

description.text:
This is an airspeed gauge prototype. The idea being the weight hangs down and the wind tab which slides into the weight and would be glued in place could be re-designed easily in testing to calibrate. Likewise the indicator weight has 3 x 6mm holes booleaned so that 6mm bolt shanks could be slid into place to add weight if needed for calibration. The idea being this would be useful for measuring airspeed in different situations however this is a design in progress so no idea if or how well it might work yet. I designed this as I fly gyroplanes and saw a similar design made of steel on a gyro. I imagine adding calibrated marks or even printing them on a sticker when finished.

However it should be noted that if using this with any aircraft such as this the risk is all yours I make no guarantee of its safety, you should consider the vibration and ability for it to fall off and fly through a propeller. Also as the airspeed indicated will be effected by angle in a gyro which climb fairly level this should not change much but during descent in which the nose if pointed down you may find this too inaccurate to be safe. For this reason I am thinking of changing this design to just incorporate a spring. However even as a hand held airspeed gauge for training purposes on the ground or in a gyroglider (towed behind a car) this may be perfectly suitable. I'd suggest a thin washer between the base and indicator to ensure free movement. It may also be suitable for hang gliders once modify to add a spring and remove the weight feel free to modify and get working. I always used a hall guage which was a tapered plastic tube with a disk and found this a good indicator a simple device like this might save some money on unnecessarily expensive guages. However gyros cannot stall and I personally was trained to fly without a gauge at all so I have a good idea of airspeed from stick feel so I wouldn't be too put out if this thing fell off. Beware though inexperienced pilots should only be using certified gauges or at least have an experienced pilot test this first.

description.text:
I have remixed my original single filament guide to accommodate printers with dual spool hangers.

Sometimes filament would unspool over the side of the spool during prints.
On longer prints this would cause print failures as the filament would eventually tighten around the arm of the spool holder.

This filament guide slides on the front the of printrbot's aluminum handle and hold the filament roughly in the center of the spool as the filament is pulled off.

The dimensions are pretty tight to the handles dimensions to ensure a snug fit.
You may need to file/carve a small amount for the initial fitting.

description.text:
fasteners for cables , for my Fiat Scudo
coPet, 0.2mm
This assembly allows the use of a spiral cut coupler on the z-axis. It uses a thrust washer assembly to eliminate leadscrew end-play, and otherwise corrects wobble in the z-axis.

If you own a Prusa, then the assembly is fairly straight forward. You will need to purchase a few items as follows: 1) Spiral cut coupler. You need two. 2) M3 x 50mm socket head screws. Easy to find online. You need 4pc. 3) 8mm I.D. thrust washers. McMaster carr P/N xxxxx (or print one) 2ea. 4) Depending on the length of your current lead screws, you may
need new ones. I didn't, but it was close. -Disassemble your machine and install parts in order as illustrated. -Use washers on the 50mm screws as needed. -Keep the whole assembly loose and separate the motor and spacer
with a couple of business cards (up to 1mm thickness). This will put
some necessary preload on the spiral cut of the coupler. -Use some moly lube on the clamping fasteners to allow even
torquing, and tighten them with a high quality hex-wrench.
You may want to also use thread locker, or epoxy glue on
both the lead screw and the motor shaft to ensure no-slip. _Finally, remove the business card shim from the assembly and
tighten the 4 long screws that hold it all together. It is important
to keep an eye on the spiral cut. It should collapse just slightly,
but not totally! That is very important. Unfortunately, I do not use openscad. I will start with .stl's and if that won't work, let me know. I use solidworks, but can export several formats... just not openscad:(

description.text:
Bigger and better version coming soon! more stretch and greater ammo capacity

Remixed rubber band gun.

This is the most reliable and simplest to print rubber band gun available. The other designs that use rotating wheels and sears are unreliable and often no more than 3-4 rubber bands can be loaded and fired reliably

A few performance tweaks and visual styling. Grip Panels and beaver tail to stop trigger mechanism from hitting the webbing of your thumb (ouch).

Snap together design, studs press into matching holes, no glue necessary.

Printed and tested
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mx-LsuR2RqU

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1-0.2

Infill:

20-30%

Notes:

Printing on Kapton tape and using some water based glue stick is a good way to get maximum build platform adhesion and stop warping.

Step 1:

Clean up parts as necessary.

Step 2:

Take the the bottom part and place it down on a firm surface with the studs sticking up.

Step 3:

Take the middle part and place it over the bottom part lining up the holes with the studs and press down firmly. A small craft hammer can help press down the parts.

Step 4:

Take the trigger and place it in the recess of the parts you have assembled. Using a small rubber band place it in the cut out formed by the middle and trigger parts.

Tip: A larger rubber band can be twisted and folded to form a smaller loop.

Step 5:

Take the top part line up the stud and hole and press down onto the assembly.

Step 6:

take the bottom grip panel and place it under the assembly lining up the studs with the holes in the grip. Then take the top grip panel and press it down firmly over the studs and down onto the assembly.

Tip: the grip panels should have a very tight fit and may need a small craft hammer to completely seat, and hold the gun together.

Ready to fire

take three rubber bands (the small kind used for bundling money work best) and load them one at a time, looping them over the cutout on the end of the barrel and then secure them over the tangs on the back of the gun near the grip. one on top of the other.

Point and shoot.

each pull of the trigger will shoot a rubber band and move the rubber bands below up read to fire.

Designed in Fusion360

I took the original design and imported it into fusion 360 and then made new drawings from the imported STL's I was then able to rebuild the gun making the changes I wanted.

The gun is small enough to fit on a 150x150mm build table, but not to small to be held by a large hand. If you have a larger printer you could scale the X and Y axes to print a large gun.

PLA @ 215 Deg C

Still in the process of documenting this build.

Bill of material is in the sketchup file, which will exclude extruder and electronics.

Updating in progress...
https://youtu.be/ly-76dTwJm4

I have been working on this build for quite some time. I was already getting good results from this printer built with printed parts. Printed parts conform to pressure and lose tension over time. Bolts become loose after a some time. I am in the process of replacing some of the printed parts with machined aluminium pieces. As can be seen from pictures posted above, part_A to part_D have been replaced. Still awaiting part_E to part_J to be delivered. Various types of corner brackets and T-slot nuts are used to hold frame and everything else to the frame.

Posted above are the stl files for printed parts which will be slightly different from machined aluminium pieces due to big difference in material strength. Only essential stl files for building this printer are posted. The rest can be generated from sketchup file and print after you have a working printer. You might want to modify them depending on the components you use.

This build was intended to be small with a target build volume of 140x140x100mm. I am getting slightly less with a bit of safety margin.

Printed this Deadpool and there is an error in the STL, the buckles on his shoulder straps are deformed or tear up during printing (noticed this in some of the "I made this" pictures also). I designed (using 123D Design) these to replace them. Simply using a sharp knife cut the old buckles off where they meet the belt and then print these. Once they are printed you may need to trim them to make them fit correctly. Now these were measured and printed for the size Deadpool that I did you may have to adjust the scaling to fit the one you print.
Trim them to fit the sides of the strap and then glue (weld with acetone if you're using ABS) them in place.

description.text: Carrier for 4 22oz bottles.

This bottle carrier can be made either with a scroll saw or a laser cutter, (Or for that matter with a cnc machine) the SVG file is optimized for cutting from a 4" x 15" x 7/32" plywood panel.
The pictured variant was scroll sawed.
After cutting it out, the assembly should be glued.
The source OpenSCAD file is fully parameteric and is easily modified to generate carriers for other size bottles and wood thicknesses (Wine, 750ml beers, and I guess 12oz bottles, but then you'd want the original 6 packer.) Although going to very thick material dimensions (more than say 1/2") will require more rejiggering of the design.

title: Eiffel Tower 199.5mm tall with nearly all detail printable at 0.4mm nozzle

description.text:
I scaled the piece to be 199.5 mm tall. This one prints nicely now on a UM2+ with extra cooling from the top of the printer to prevent further warping. You could also print it at 200c to reduce warping, but at it might give you poor adhesion on the very small struts, specially the top section.
I'd recommend 210c with extra fan cooling from the top of the printer to prevent warping of all the small struts.

I've altered the fences on the first level so the slicer 'sees' them and now they print properly with a 0.4mm nozzle.

comments.text: Greetings!  This is a wonderful Thing and I thank you for it.  Can you (or someone else) suggest ways to reduce the coarse texture on the structure?  My results are similar to yours'. Right now I'm printing it on my Delta printer (DIY) with a 0.4 nozzle and 0.15 layer height.  Would a slower print speed matter?  How about a smaller nozzle (0.3)?  I'm probably seeking the impossible but then, that's what I do...
comments.author: Loftonharris

comments.text:
Hi! Well you can try for sure with a 0.3 or 0.25 nozzle and perhaps even go for 100u layer height.
The real solution would be to scale it further up as many do and slice it on one of the platforms.
With this scale it is really about finding the limits on X,Y and Z accuracy with those smaller trusses.

remixed_from.author: ChrisParish
remixed_from.title: Kossel Mini spool holder featuring Emmett's gear bearing.

title: Kossel mini spool bearing for BQ,ESUN,3DPlastX, CoLiDo etc

description.text:
When I bought a CoLiDo reel I discovered that my previous bearing/spool holder was too small and the reel was hitting the bottom structure of the spool holder from ChrisParish.

So I designed an improved spool holder, with a taller, wider base, almost "universal" for my reels.

It's 51mm in diameter so it can fit the smallest reel from ESUN that I have. Without any other support it's ok for ESUN,BQ and CoLiDo reel (tested).

With an optional support you can use it even for 3DPlastX reel.

The emmet's bearing is made with 0.2mm tolerance.

In the middle you can fit an M3 nut. You could need an hammer to fit the nut inside. (or a wrench)

I printed mine in red CoLiDo PLA.

title: Hood Scoop Mini with double turbines

description.text:
Toys for big boyz. We used to put small propellers on the handlebars of our bicycles when we were small. Now we got older but we can still do the same thing to our cars or motorbikes. I've been designing some toys of this kind recently and this is the mini version of my double hood scoop.
it has holes below for magnets along with suction channels. Because of the suction generated by these channels the thing sticks to the surface more as it goes faster thru the air. Can be used on metal surfaces of vehicles or stationary objects. I installed only 6 small magnets and tested the thing up to 110km/h without problems. If you want you may increase or decrease the number of magnets. leave the magnet holes connected the main turbine channel empty as they will create more suction while moving. The turbines are connected to the body via mini ball bearings inside so you can use it for years.
https://youtu.be/GdPzdSDHvDM
https://www.facebook.com/ozkal.ozsoy/videos/vb.701145747/10153782451105748/?type=3&theater

print_settings.Notes:: Printed in ABS.  Recommend the "grid" support structure if you're slicing with Cura or similar.

description.text:
This is a track connector for my son's Hot Wheels track. We bought it at a toy sale and some of the connectors were missing, so I designed this replacement.

It's an awkward print as it has bits that stick out on both the top and bottom. I suggest that you print it as oriented on a grid support so that just the retaining pin points downwards. Then the support can be removed relatively cleanly. I recommend a full grid support because the layer above the support is only 1.2mm thick.

description.text:
This is the big version of the Speedy Red Swept Wing.
It has now a wingspan of 1510 mm and weights 1250 grams.
Like the small wing, all sections of this big one were only hold together by two cords inside the tubes.They are fixed with luster terminals on the wing ends.
Only the two red middle sections, each consisting of 4 parts, are glued together.
This should have the big advantage to print and exchange only a very few parts - in case of crash.
It seems that this method is not secure enough for this big plane. And as you can see on the video, it finally crashes.
It would have been better if the parts were glued together. Now there are some more parts to print...
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mUGuW6KuunY
Unfortunately, the camera got lost during the second flight. Most likely when it started to flutter, just before the crash. It was only fixed with velcro tape. I miss much more the videos than the camera itself.

Update 8.October 2016
Helmut, who also printed the motor sailplane http://www.thingiverse.com/make:158813
was so kind to share his parts of the splitted fuselage with the associated interfaces.
The biggest part is now 160 mm.
Thank you Helmut.

Here is a video of his own printed airplane https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KQO3qlDL3Ts

Update 23. January 2018
Upload large fin, though I think it is not necessary.
fin 140.stl
fin cap 140.stl

Print Settings
Attention
The wings are designed to print with 0.5 width, 0.3 hight and 3 bottom and top layer
If you print thinner, the perimeter of the upper side will not merge with the perimeter of the inner spars.
If you print thicker, the perimeter will not be printed continuesly in one turn.
The print must go as if you print in spiral vase mode. So you reach at least a smooth surface on the upper side.
If needed, you must try with 0.49 or 0.48 width. It depends on which slicer you use.
The second thing is, if you print with less layer hight, the inner spars will not connect the top and the bottom layer. There will be a gap inbetween.

All parts: layer height =0,3mm, width =0.5 mm
wing
1 perimeter, 3 bottom layer, 3 top layer, hollow
wing servo: 3 bottom layer, 3 top layer, hollow
elevon base: 5 bottom layer, spiral vase mode
elevon: 3 bottom layer, spiral vase mode
elevon interface: no bottom layer, spiral vase mode
elevon horn: 10 bottom layer, 60% infill

fuselage
fuselage front: 7 bottom layer, 3 top layer, 40% infill
fuselage middle: 1 bottom layer, 1 top layer, hollow
fuselage back: 3 bottom layer, 3 top layer, 40% infill
fuselage interface: 2 perimeter 0.4 no bottom/top layer, holow
fin: 5 bottom layer, spiral vase mode
fin cap: 2 bottom layer, 40% infill

Update 08/07/2016
I just noticed that the middle wing parts have an offset of 0.7mm to the outer wing.
I deleted the files and upload the modified parts with added "mod"

Update 10/8/2016
Helmut, who also printed the motor sailplane http://www.thingiverse.com/make:158813
was so kind to share his parts of the splitted fuselage with the associated interfaces.
They are splitted in 4 pieces, the biggest part now is 160 mm.
Thank you Helmut.

Update 10/10/2016
I added templates to align the splitted wing parts of the middle section. Print as much as possible of a template, position it diagonal and shorten only the front of it.
Furthermore, they are important to get exactly the same hole spacing for the plug in mounts.

Update Oct 23, 2016
Servo cables
Attention! before gluing the middle wing segments, the openings for the cables must be cut out. If the edges are welded with a soldering iron, the interrupted print structure is connected.
For the opening on the fuselage you can use a the cover frame (cable cover frame)

Update Jan. 18, 2017
Uploaded wing_rear_center_mod2160
At the previous file were lacking three top layers.

Aligning the middle wing segments
Not only the wing profile has to be aligned, but also the hole spacing for the connections must fit exactly.
For both, I uploaded templates:
template center at the root,
template 160 mm at the inner connection
template 320 mm at the outer connection
Print as much of the stencils as possible (diagonal). shorten it only on the front.(netfabb)
If a larger gap occurs (because of shrinking) between the groove and the spring, it must be filled with glue.

Connectors 6 mm carbon tube
The holes for the connections are only parallel:

  1. In the middle, between the wing halves (99 mm in each side, 198 mm total)
    In addition, reinforce these tubes with 4 mm carbon tubes glued into the inside!
  2. At the servo segment (50 mm in the middle wing and 37 mm in the outer wing (133 mm total)
  3. At the wing end (29 mm in the wing and 40 mm in the wing end (69 mm total)

The pipes must not be inserted deeper. There the holes bend and break very easily if you go deeper!

All other connectors are not parallel, that means, you have to plug in the tubes one after the other, and see that you can get them out again, if needed. If both pipes are inside, the wings can not be pulled apart!

Between the two middle wing parts I recommend 60 mm deep plugs (120 mm total)
Between the outer wing parts, I recommend 40 mm deep plugs (80 mm total)

The wing end can be left plugged and, for example, secure them with screws.
All other parts have to be glued and not only fasten with strings! (see video)

I will try not to glue the middle plugging, so that the wing remains plugged into two halves.
For this purpose, I want to make the centering blocks under the wings thicker, so that one can turn a screw in each block. Then clamp together these two screws with rubber bands. (see new image)

Specifications
airfoil: KN209838/HM50T10% - twist: -4.5°
wing span: 1510 mm
wing chord: 259.5/195 mm
aerodynamic center: 116 mm (12%)
overall weight: 1250 g
wing weight: 716 g
fuselage weight 146 g
fin weight 12 g
wing area: 34.9 dm²
wing loading: 36 g/dm²
longitudinal stability (Thies) STFs:
motor: Robbe Roxxy BL Outrunner 2834-08
static thrust: 1000 g (3S Lipo)
battery: Turnigy 1800 mAh 3S 40~50C Lipo
motor camber: -4°
side pull: no
propeller: Aeronaut CAM Aeronaut Carbon Classic 10 x 6"

comments.text: Flew it this weekend.  CG of ~120 felt good to me.  First flight a friend launched it with out issue.  Flew nice and stable, I did feel that the yaw axis was not real stable maybe a bigger rudder would help otherwise it flew great.  On mine I glued the entire wing together and was able to do loops, rolls and high speed passes without any structural issues.  Stall with full elevator was stable with a slight roll to the left. Slowed nicely for landing.  Around a 5 minute flight.

title: Manatee Humerus Bone - High Resolution Scan

description.text:
This is a scan of a real Florida MANATEE (family Trichechidae, genus Trichechus) humerus (arm bone). Manatees are the state mammal of Florida, and are an endangered species. This on is on loan to me from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission and is curated at the Department of Anthropology at Indiana University South Bend. Most manatee bones are solid cortical bone, giving them a great density. Since manatees arms have evolved into flippers, the bones of the upper arm and forearm have an unusual shape.

This specimen measures approximately 8", and is a juvenile female. Print it in parts, or scale down to fit your bed. Scanned with NextEngine scanner.

Print this unusual and rare specimen, use it for teaching, or simply educate yourself about zoology. Comment me for proper attribution if used in any other manner than personal. Not for commercial use.

Please post a photo to share if you print this, and check out my other scans of skulls and bones at http://www.thingiverse.com/dricketts/designs.

Be sure to "Like" my Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/FetalReproductions to subscribe to my current prints/blogs, and see my Etsy page at http://Etsy.com/FetalReproductions for baby fetal scans, skulls, and other items to own.

title: Stabilized Roll Axis Canard Rocket [NAZE32 Board]

description.text:
The roll actuation module was designed in AutoCAD. The module was designed to
be a section of the rocket’s external airframe. I also included an exhaust manifold that allowed the parachute charge to flow through the module. It was 3D printed and the 12 gram digital metal gear servos were installed in their compartment. The 2.4 GHz receiver, 850mAh 7.4 volt battery, and the SBEC (power supply) were installed in the module. The NAZE32 quadcopter flight control board was then installed over the other components. The tricopter tail servo firmware was used to control the fins. The two canard fins were designed with AutoCAD and 3D printed using carbon fiber filament. The carbon fiber increases strength and rigidity, but decreases flexibility, which is required for this application. The canard fins were screwed onto servo horns. The wires were connected to the control board and the PID (proportional, integral, derivative) loop was tuned. For the first launch, the PID values were, P: 4, I: 0.045, D: 1. The (AltimeterThree) altimeter/accelerometer was attached above the control NAZE32 in order to collect flight data.

comments.text: Have you considered extending this to all 4 fins?
comments.author: SkyRider

comments.text: Yes, I would like to use four fins. I would have to custom program a PID controller for pitch, roll, and yaw.
comments.author: SkyRider

comments.text: I wonder how well you could add to this design to allow the rocket first to fly straight and then so long as you have a suitable delay charge, allow it to self guide towards a specific area near its takeoff point and subsequently actuate a servo release of the parachute like the ChuteRelease.  This way, no matter how high the rocket goes, and how far, it would, essentially attempt to return and open the parachute, say, at 300' AGL.
comments.author: AeroScience

comments.text: I have had similar ideas. It seems possible, but the PID controller would have to be tuned dynamically, based off of velocity, to ensure accuracy. Since the rocket, using gyros, would only know its position relative to the launch pad, the error could add up quickly. If a GPS was used, this problem could be eliminated. Otherwise, it is a great idea, and I would definitely like to try it if I have the time and resources.
comments.author: SkyRider

comments.text: Maybe it can be a joint project.  I would love to test this on one of my rockets.  We could add it as a section so that the rocket splits with the nose and the module attached and so is never exposed to ejection gases....or we could try this module I have been working on for large rockets that ejects to the rear.  Waiting on Apogee to publish it.

title: uStepper Nema23 bracket
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A Nema23 bracket for the uStepper. The uStepper is originally designed to fit on a Nema17 stepper motor, but has the capability to run a Nema23, so therefore I made a bracket for it!
On the back of the Nema 23 there should be 4 holes spaced 32mm on one side and 51mm on the other side (center to center). These four holes should be M3 and with a depth of 1.8mm.

See a video of uStepper doing closed loop control on a 3D printer (with Nema17 though) here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oidiMjSqiBU

Switching to an application using Nema23 does not change anything with regards to the feedback algorithm, making it possible to use also on larger machines.

Or visit www.uStepper.com for more info.

description.text:
This is a basic spool holder specifically designed to fit onto a Printrbot Simple Metal Z Axis guide rail. Its designed so that you don't need to use a ton of plastic to print out a spool holder.

There are two parts:

The Spool Holder
The Filament Retainer Bar

The angle of the spool holder keeps the spool on the spool peg.
The retainer bar can be used either with the long or short leg in the spool slot so it can be used with "most" filament spools.
The retainer bar prevents the filament from wrapping around your z guide rails.

THE FILAMENT RETAINER BAR NEEDS TO BE USED OTHERWISE FILAMENT WILL WRAP AROUND THE Z GUIDE RAILS AND MESS YOUR PRINT UP! Believe me, its happened twice to me: one time wasting almost a whole print, the second time the filament snapped, breaking at the very top of the extruder assembly. It was a pain to get it out. So I redesigned it to have this filament retainer bar!

Assembly:

Just pop the Spool Holder onto the Z Axis Guide Rail.
Slip the Filament Retainer bar into the Spool Holder's upper slot.
Drop your roll onto the Spool Holder making sure the filament feeds from the top.
Make sure the Filament Retainer Bar Covers the whole filament area of the spool so that the filament is "retained" in the area between the spool of filament and the filament retainer bar.

Yer done!

description.text:
Replacement Cone Thread Holder for Brother Sewing Machine
I created this for my mom as her original was old, brittle and cracking.

There are 2 parts to this:

  1. The 'plate' on which the thread cone sits
  2. The 'spindle' that is inserted into the thread cone to stabilize it on the rod.

There are 2 versions of the spindle
a. With slots - this is a replica of the original part, but can be brittle when 3D printed
b. Without slots - a much stronger part when 3D printed

These printed very nicely on my Printrbot Metal
Unfortunately I forgot to take a photo of the printed parts before mailing to mom :(

author: craigj

description.text:
Well, it's that time of the year when we like to go Camping, and after a smelly evening in front of a BBQ and spilt beer we need a shower, right ?.
So off we go to the shower block and into the shower cubicle, to be faced with a push vavle on the wall that gives you enough water to water a small plant, before it pops out and off we go again - press the valve and another small dribble of water appears, it's enough to give you RSI.
So, print this little device that I designed, slip it over the valve, twist to lock it on, this will lock the button in and hey presto - enough water to fill an Olympic swimming pool - just don't forget to remove it when your skin has gone all wrinkly and you have finished.
Enjoy your showers from now on !

Very hard puzzle to make.
You can print the textured or untextured one.
Happy printing.

description.header: Project: Visual proof to the volume formula of a pyramid
description.text:
project name:

Visual proof to the volume formula of a pyramid

Overview & Background:

: I am a student. I have recently taken geometry. I happen to be a visual special person so I loved it is definitely by far my favorite math. Some people in my class didn’t find it as easy as I did. I think this is for one main reason it is quite difficult to visualize all of these concepts in your head. They seemed to find it much easier when my teacher had visual models of these concepts. So I created a few 3D models of them. When I saw this challenge I decided I would publish one of them and this is the one I chose. It is a model depicting visually why the formula for the volume of a pyramid works. Although this model simplifies it a great deal it still illustrates the concept. The model is three congruent pyramids that fit together to create a cube. Since the formula for a pyramid’s volume is 1/3Bh and a cube is just Bh it is clear that the formula works

Objectives:

The objective is to demonstrate the formula of the volume of a pyramid

Audiences:

Geometry students

Subjects:

Geometry

Skills Learned (Standards):

The ability to find the volume of a pyramid and understand why it works.

Lesson/Activity:

Teach the formula of the volume of a pyramid but using this model as a visual aid.

Duration:

20 minutes

Preparation:

Print the model!

comments.text: Taught math for 6 years and my wife still does. Printing this right now, just cause it makes me smile. #Applications of Math and 3d printing. =) #win

description.text:
This is a Camera Tripod mount adaptor for the 3D printed AstroPi Flight case from the Raspberry Pi Foundation (https://www.raspberrypi.org/learning/3d-printed-astro-pi-flight-case/).

The mount attaches to the AstroPi through the corner bolts but, due to the extra thickness of the arms, you'll need some slightly longer bolts (I'm using 35mm ones). Once installed the AstroPi can be attached to any standard 1/4" tripod mount.

I've included two variants of the mount. The 'threaded' variant has the screw thread as part of the model, requiring no extra parts, but may be a little trickier to print successfully. I've found it a little stiff to attach the first time, but then is easier to attach/remove.

The alternative model is the 'Nut' variant which has a space for inserting a 1/4" UNC nut for bolting to a tripod. This should, in theory, be an easier print, however you will need to source an appropriate nut to finish things off. Hopefully they have a somewhat standard outside dimensions, but for reference the ones I purchased can be found on ebay (http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/260467071167)

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Mono Mendel

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

30%

Notes:

For my printer I used a brim to stop the arms from lifting (Printing onto a heated glass bed)

I printed the 'threaded' variant at 0.1mm, other layer heights may or may not work.

description.text:
FolgerTech FT-5 Dual Extrusion Modifications using two E3D v6 and Titans.

This was just a test file to see how it would fit and only has been printer to test size and how much reduction in print size it would be on the FolgerTech FT-5.

7/18/2016

V 2 now places the stepper motors under the railing.

10/18/2016

Updated pictures to the new mount. Finally finished wiring the FT-5 and can test out the design. Lost about 60mm of travel on the x-axis. Wiring is a mess and needs to have some improvements. Need a bigger cable chain to fit extra wires.

Notes

Firmware changes will have to be done by the user.
Might be better to go with bowden design.

Printer:

Custom

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

40

comments.author: thelongrunsmoke

comments.text: Nema 17/Short Body/13Ncm
comments.author: thelongrunsmoke

comments.text: There is enough torque?
comments.author: YeaYuh

comments.text: Should be fine.  I'm using a Titan + 13Ncm motor w/ a Volcano on another printer and haven't had any issues.
comments.author: thelongrunsmoke

comments.text:
I was following Tom's advice but haven't tested it yet.
Tomas Sanladerer : Titan Review - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tiAQ9slUZ58
comments.author: thelongrunsmoke

comments.text:
AFAIK, the FT-5 has the filament extruder stepper under the X rail.
Would like to get an FT-5 myself, except it needs dual extruders so I can do HIPS support. Most likely I'd use a dual flexion for space savings
https://flexionextruder.com/shop/
.
Like where you're going with this and if you could post how you get it wired. With dual Z and Y steppers thought the driver board was already fully populated. In my opinion, the Z could be done with a single stepper as it doesn't take much effort to raise/lower the print bed with the lead screws, and isn't constant duty like the X and Y.
comments.author: Prot0typ1cal

comments.text: The board does still have a free slot for a second extruder.  You wire each set of motors for the Z and Y to be in parallel.

description.text:
This strategy game is a plain classic! It can be played by rather small children, and mastered by adults as it's a two-player game with perfect information.

To create the swivel foot makes the construction easy to store.

The build was done on a desktop cnc-machine from Stepcraft from 6.5 mm beech plywood using a spiral-toothed 1.2 mm flute. The funnel walls are made from 3 mm poplar plywood. I did cut them with a cutter knife, just because it was much faster. The dark gaming pieces are colored by wood stain, the white ones with acrylic spray-paint.

Visit https://www.zenziwerken.de/en/ for more interesting designs.

With this rough sketch I worked out the basic principle of the swivel foot. Using Solid Edge 2D I created the 3-side-view. As all parts are 2D the result is already the production data. The red lines show the position of the game pieces and the initial geometry. Then I made a 3d-model to get an impression of the design.

remixed_from.title: My Customized OpenSCAD Threadless Ballscrew - Highly

title: Threadless Ballscrew Nut (5 degree tilt for 16mm shaft)

description.text:
This is another design for threadless ballscrew nut.

The nut relies on friction of the shaft and bearings to grip, and move by turning the nut or the shaft.

You'll need:

  1. M6 x 47mm screws x3
  2. M6 x 20mm screw x1
  3. M6 x 11mm x 1mm spacers x6
  4. M6 nuts x3 (or x6 if you want to "lock" the nuts in place)
  5. M6 square nut x1
  6. 626 bearings x6

You want to print 2 identical pieces and put the back-to-back, place the square nut in the slot for the adjustment screw, and screw the bearings and "tension adjustment screw" in.

To make spacers, I just pick up some M6 washers, secure a stack of them onto a M6 screw with nut, put them on a drill, and turn down the outer diameter with a grinder.
If you don't have a grinder, you can use some sandpaper to do the job.

You want the spacers to avoid the outer bearing ring (and maybe the sealing cap?) to grind against the printed ballscrew nut, and with some support under the bearing you can tighten the screws with greater force, thus better secure the nuts in place.

The 2 screw holes for the fixed bearings are a bit tight, you just tap them when you screw them in.

as a bonus, you can loosen the adjustment screws so you can slide the nut around the shaft, acts as a "quick release" like what you have on a lathe :-D

The tested nut

The nut I printed (shown in the picture) sustained my full body weight (approx 55kg), I can't get it to slip even I apply nearly my full weight onto it.

It's 5 degree tilt angle on a 16mm shaft, according to calculation it should travel about 4.397mm per revolution, with my (cheap Chinese) digital caliper it traveled around 4.66mm per revolution, I think the error is introduced by:

  1. the play on the bearing
  2. resolution of the printing (I'm printing with 0.2mm layer height on a Flashforge Creator Pro)
  3. the cheap Chinese caliper... got it for like USD$15...... you can't really count on that.

The math behind revolution and nut movement:

  1. let the tilt angle of the ball bearing be ϴ
  2. let the diameter of the shaft be D
  3. the circumferences of the shaft be C = D x π
  4. the movement of the nut after full revolution be H

given the angle ϴ and shaft diameter D

the movement of the nut per revolution is:
H = tan(ϴ) x D x π

for example:

  1. a 8mm shaft with 20 degree ball bearing angle will travel
    H= tan(20 degree) x 8mm * π ~= 0.364 x 8mm x 3.1415 ~= 9.147mm
    after a full revolution.
  2. a 8mm shaft with 10 degree ball bearing angle will travel
    H = tan(10 degree) x 8mm * π ~= 0.176 x 8mm x 3.1415 ~= 4.4315mm
    after a full revolution.
  3. a 16mm shaft with 10 degree ball bearing angle will travel
    H = tan(10 degree) x 16mm x π ~= 0.176 x 16mm x 3.1415 ~= 8.8631mm
    after a full revolution.

given the shaft diameter D and desired travel distance H

the tilt angle of the ball bearing should be
ϴ = tan^-1(H / (D x π))

for example,

  1. you want the nut to travel 4mm after a full revolution with a 16mm shaft, go for
    ϴ = tan^-1(4 / (16 x π)) ~= tan^-1(0.00795) ~= 4.55 degree

description.text:
This is remixed version of Anna which is possible to print without any pain; at the end - it is HARD to print, but it is achievable.

UPDATE: The Bigger version (scaled to the 190%) takes really BIG amount of filament - I've currently ~36% printed and it has taken around 65m of filament; so keep eye on your roll!

UPDATE II: If the first layer is not OK, try to move model around -0.5mm down under a bed; this can help to propertly print the first layer.

UPDATE III: If you want to print bigger version, check if you have enough filament; my final result weights 400g with supports, ~300g without them; you can guess where I was out of filament.

Printer:

Prusa i3 MK2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.15

Infill:

30%

Notes:
  • You can omit bottom layer (it is recommanded because model itself is a bit buggy)
  • I've used 4 shells (3 ia enough)
  • ~5 top layers
  • I've scaled model to 190% of the original (it's almost 20cm in height)
  • Infill was set to honeycomb

UPDATE: I'm not sure, 30% of infill on 190% scale is pretty much, maybe 20-25% will be enough.

author: 3daybreaker

print_settings.Notes:: With accurate extrusion I found that the threads worked well at .2mm

description.text:
I needed a spool to share some filament with a friend so I sat down and designed one. I know there are a few others but I wanted something that was 100% printable, no added hardware, and had some ideas in my head.

There is a short and long hub version - depending on your filament holder the long version may be better to keep the arms from catching.

Printer:

Monoprice Maker Select (Wanhao i3)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

20

Notes:

Print one Hub (regular or long), one Side, one Nut and 3 arms. Lay all items flat for printing, hub with threaded part up.

Be very careful of over extrusion - the threads are high precision. If you find the nut will not thread on to the hub, you may be over extruding - reduce your flow rate slightly.

With accurate extrusion I found that the threads worked well at .2mm
Designed in Fusion 360

title: camera hot shoe to keep on
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
You know the feeling, perhaps: everything ready and in position on the tripod, battery empty.
Or: I just want to see how the last picture turned out.
In both cases I had to remove my "old" Panasonic DMC-FZ5 from the tripod and the hot shoe, disturbing the great angle/postition, before I could get to the battery or the SD-card.

Not any more. With this gadget I can get to both without disturbing anything.

Printer:

Prusa i3 (Hesine, originally ;-))

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0,2

Infill:

30%

Notes:

Standing it upright was the best way to minimize the support-"damage".
Support was with the same PLA.
Not a very nice print, but I was the first one with a new filament. so some adjustments need to be made. It was good enough, though, to make it a very useful gadget. ;-)

Took some measurements from my old shoe etc. and puzzled it together in FreeCAD.
RepetierHost and Slic3r were so kind as to do the rest.

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
These are a series of Magnets I made after doing a lot of driving across the country this past month.

Which symbols do you, your friends, or/and your family look for when you are getting away from the city?

I also have them for sale on my Etsy store

I have added a PDF of State and National Park Symbols. If there is one you really want that I have not already added here let me know, I have got a pretty solid system down to make generate them ;)

Notes:

These have 2 color changes printing at .2layer height (.4 first layer)

First 3 layers are Petg White, Then all brown ABS, and the final 4 layers are back at Petg White.

author: jephil08

description.text: Scanned with the MakerBot Digitizer Desktop 3D Scanner

comments.text: Looks nice, Some suggestions, you never want to have any background too close to the scanner. It's all about the laser not getting distorted. If you have a background too close, there is a possibility of it reflecting off the background and hitting the laser that is actually scanning the object, laser distorting lasers, can get inaccurate results. It's not about having the object white, it's about dulling the color so there is no reflection or distortion. Hope this helps. Of course I would be commenting on something that came out really nice.
comments.author: NenZilla

comments.text: Thanks for the suggestions, my students were just grabbing anything and everything yesterday to push the limits of the scanner.  My biggest feature request right now is either exporting of just the point cloud or being able to do low-res "quick scans" when testing out object orientation.  I'm sure some of these features will be rolled out in the coming months.
